fleet: honor Retry-After on push, jitter the push tick, extra regressions, namespace pre-req warning

Five related changes on top of commit 3715aed, all surfaced by the
post-audit review of the push path + chart installation story.

Honor Retry-After on 429/503 push responses
  The GET poller (fleet_client.go) already parsed Retry-After on
  rate-limit / service-unavailable responses and advanced its next
  tick accordingly. The POST push path (emitter.go) ignored the
  header entirely: every non-2xx collapsed into a single statusErr
  and the loop pushed again at the regular interval. Under a real
  Fleet overload — the exact scenario where Retry-After exists —
  hundreds of agents would keep hammering a server asking them to
  back off.

  - internal/health/retryafter.go (new): shared parseRetryAfterHeader
    helper returning (Duration, ok). Also exports a typed
    RetryAfterError with StatusCode + Delay, and an AsRetryAfter
    convenience for errors.As callers.
  - internal/health/emitter.go: doPush on 429 or 503 reads the
    header; when present, returns *RetryAfterError instead of the
    plain status error. Other 4xx / 5xx paths unchanged.
  - internal/health/fleet_client.go: parseRetryAfter delegates to
    the shared helper, keeping its FallbackBackoff default.
  - internal/health/loop.go: tick() now returns the server-requested
    backoff (0 when none); TickOnce() surfaces it for tests; Run()
    adds that backoff to the next timer delay so ctx cancellation
    during backoff still exits promptly.

Jitter the push-loop ticker
  N agents launched by the same Helm rollout used to synchronize
  push ticks forever because time.NewTicker is deterministic. Run()
  now uses a self-driven time.Timer seeded from each Loop's own rng,
  spreading subsequent ticks by ±10% around PushInterval. The Loop
  struct gains an rng field seeded per-instance so two Loops in the
  same process draw independent sequences. A nextDelay helper folds
  the jitter + any outstanding Retry-After backoff into one call.

Regression tests
  - TestPush_429RetryAfterSeconds, TestPush_503RetryAfterHTTPDate:
    both RFC 7231 forms produce a RetryAfterError with the right
    Delay. 20 s HTTP-date has ±5 s slack for test-runtime jitter.
  - TestPush_429NoRetryAfterIsPlainError,
    TestPush_400RetryAfterIsPlainError: a missing header and a
    non-{429,503} status with header MUST fall through to the plain
    status-error path. Otherwise a hypothetical future change could
    over-reach and treat any Retry-After as backoff.
  - TestPush_TCPResetIsRetriedAsNetworkError: a hijacker-based server
    that sets SO_LINGER=0 and closes mid-handshake produces an EPIPE
    / EOF / ECONNRESET depending on timing. The test asserts all
    three shapes hit the one-jittered-retry path (elapsed >= 100 ms)
    and do NOT look like a status error.
  - TestPush_BlackholeDialRespectsTimeout: point the emitter at a
    no-longer-listening port, assert the push fails inside
    cfg.Timeout plus slack. Guards against future dialer-timeout
    drift that would let a SYN-dropped packet block for the
    kernel's ~63 s default.
  - New newRetryAfterServer helper isolates the "recording server +
    header injection" case from newRecordingServer to keep each
    helper narrow.

Installation-time namespace pre-req in NOTES
  deploy/helm/ingero/templates/NOTES.txt: when namespace.create=false
  the rendered notes now warn that the agent runs a privileged
  container and the target namespace MUST carry
  pod-security.kubernetes.io/enforce=privileged or admission will
  reject the DaemonSet. The chart's own namespace template already
  labels correctly when create=true; this closes the silent
  failure mode for operators installing into a pre-existing
  namespace that defaults to baseline or restricted.

Verified: full internal/health suite green locally and under
`go test -race -count=1`. The four new push-path tests pass along
with the pre-existing poller Retry-After tests that now route
through the shared helper.
